com.inqwell.any.channel

Class HttpTunnel

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractAny
      • com.inqwell.any.channel.AbstractChannelDriver
        • com.inqwell.any.channel.HttpTunnel
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, ChannelDriver, Serializable

    public class HttpTunnel
extends AbstractChannelDriver
implements ChannelDriver
    A channel driver that forms output into an HTTP POST request and awaits input from an issued HTTP GET request. Output: The channel traffic is buffered until flushOutput is called, when the POST request is formed placing the data in the message body with the appropriate content length.

    Serialized Form

    • Constructor Detail

      • HttpTunnel

        public HttpTunnel(String httpCommand,
                  URL url,
                  int port,
                  boolean encrypted)
           throws AnyException
        Create a channel driver that will operate to the given URL. The traffic will be encoded/decoded as serialized objects using the Inq standard replacements specified in Globals.

        A HttpTunnel constructed in this way will initiate the HTTP GET or POST request. A GET request is used to open a connection to an Inq server allowing the server to send messages when it is ready to do so. A POST request is used to send messages from client to server. In general, two separate connections are used to provide asynchronous, bi-directional communication as used by Inq channels. A single HttpTunnel is used for both sent and received messages to establish a session ID.

        Parameters:
        httpCommand - one of HttpTunnel.POST or HttpTunnel.GET
        url - the URL for this HTTP request
        port - the port number for the connection (required if the default port is being used)
        Throws:
        AnyException

      • HttpTunnel

        public HttpTunnel(Socket s,
                  boolean encrypted)
           throws AnyException
        Create a channel driver around a given Socket. The traffic will be encoded/decoded as serialized objects using the Inq standard replacements specified in Globals.

        A HttpTunnel is constructed around a socket accepted from an incoming connection and may act as an incoming channel (from which we can read messages) or an outgoing channel (to which we can send messages).

        Throws:
        AnyException
